ed in Spain and Northern Morocco in years past as integral to the survival strategies of Spanish Jews, who used them to make sense of the confusing and harrowing circumstances of the Spanish Civil War, the Francoist repression, and World War Two. Jewish Spain takes its place among other works on Muslims, Christians, and Jews by providing a comprehensive analysis of Jewish culture and presence in twentieth-century Spain, reminding us that it is impossible to understand and articulate what Spain was, is, and will be without taking into account both "Muslim Spain" and "Jewish Spain."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCollective memoryzSpainxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszSpainxHistoryy20th century. 0aJews, SpanishxHistoriography. 0aSephardimxHistoriography. 4aHolocaust. 4aJewish. 4aMediterranean. 4aSephardim. 4aSpain. 4aanti-Semitism. 4aconvivencia. 4aexile. 4amemory. 4aphilo-Sephardism. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804791885zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804791885423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804791885.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles